                                                                                                               GM ties up with Reva
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                          Karl Slym and Chetan Maini in New Delhi on Thursday. Picture by Ramakant Kushwaha                                  
	New Delhi, Sept. 24: General Motors of the US has turned to Indias Reva for an electric-car version of its compact Spark.         
	The two companies, which announced a tie-up today, are looking at both the domestic and the overseas markets for the electric car.        
	Within 12 months from today, we will have the car on the road. We are beginning our electric car venture with Reva on the existing GM platform and the first car will be an electric Chevrolet Spark, said Karl Slym, president and managing director of GM India.        
	Later, the U-VA as well as the new mini car  scheduled to be launched later this year  may also see electric versions, said Slym.        
	The company has started working on test vehicles and is undertaking a feasibility study.        
	We sell about 40,000 units of the Spark per annum. In addition to these, the company will sell about 4,000-6,000 of the electric version of the Spark, Ankush Arora, vice-president (marketing amp; sales) of GM India, said.         
	Chetan Maini, deputy chairman and chief technology officer of Reva Electric Car Company, said the electric Spark would be available in a series of battery options and price points.        
	Maini did not give any price details but said the car will definitely be very affordable.                                                                                                                                        
